<!-- BLOG MODALS -->
<div class="modal" id="m-b1" data-t="r"><div class="modal-bg" onclick="CM('m-b1')"></div><div class="modal-box"><div class="m-accent"></div><div class="m-hdr"><button class="m-close" onclick="CM('m-b1')">✕</button><span class="m-tag">Geopolitics · Technology · Essay 01</span><h2 class="m-title">The Geopolitics of AI Chip Wars</h2><p class="m-sub">How semiconductor export restrictions are redrawing the map of global technological power</p><div class="bmr"><span class="bm">📅 Mar 2026</span><span class="bm">⏱ 6 min</span><span class="bm">Semiconductors · India</span></div></div><div class="m-prog" id="mp-b1"></div><div class="m-body"><div class="prose"><p>When the United States imposed sweeping export controls on advanced semiconductors to China in 2022, it wasn't merely a trade policy decision — it was a declaration that the most consequential battlefield of the 21st century is measured in nanometers.</p><h3>Why Chips Are the New Oil</h3><p>For most of the 20th century, control over oil reserves defined geopolitical leverage. Today, advanced semiconductors — specifically high-end GPUs and AI accelerators — occupy that same strategic position.</p><blockquote>The most powerful AI chips are designed in California, manufactured in Taiwan using Dutch lithography machines, assembled across East Asia — a supply chain so distributed that disrupting any single node sends shockwaves everywhere.</blockquote><h3>India's Position</h3><p>For India, semiconductor geopolitics create both threat and opportunity. The India Semiconductor Mission is attracting foundry investments from companies seeking to diversify away from Taiwan-centric risk.</p><h3>The Long Game</h3><p>China's response is a multi-hundred-billion-dollar push toward semiconductor self-sufficiency. The AI chip wars are the opening moves in a longer contest over who controls the fundamental infrastructure of intelligence itself.</p></div></div></div></div>

<div class="modal" id="m-b2" data-t="r"><div class="modal-bg" onclick="CM('m-b2')"></div><div class="modal-box"><div class="m-accent"></div><div class="m-hdr"><button class="m-close" onclick="CM('m-b2')">✕</button><span class="m-tag">Defence · India · Essay 02</span><h2 class="m-title">India's Defence Tech Renaissance</h2><p class="m-sub">Domestic defence startups, drone warfare, and Atmanirbhar Bharat ambitions</p><div class="bmr"><span class="bm">📅 Feb 2026</span><span class="bm">⏱ 7 min</span></div></div><div class="m-prog" id="mp-b2"></div><div class="m-body"><div class="prose"><p>In 2020, India announced a negative import list for 101 defence items — now grown to 400+ categories. This wasn't just procurement policy — it was an industrial strategy that fundamentally altered India's defence ecosystem.</p><h3>The Startup Factor</h3><p>iDEX has funded 300+ startups working on counter-drone systems, AI surveillance, quantum communication, and hypersonic research. Several have achieved field deployment with Indian armed forces.</p><blockquote>The most significant shift is cultural. Defence procurement in India has historically been slow. The new generation of defence startups is forcing a speed-of-execution conversation the establishment is reluctantly beginning to have.</blockquote><h3>The Drone Revolution</h3><p>Ukraine and Nagorno-Karabakh demonstrated that drone warfare has permanently changed conventional conflict. India's Drone Rules 2021 catalysed an industry that barely existed three years ago.</p></div></div></div></div>

<div class="modal" id="m-b3" data-t="r"><div class="modal-bg" onclick="CM('m-b3')"></div><div class="modal-box"><div class="m-accent"></div><div class="m-hdr"><button class="m-close" onclick="CM('m-b3')">✕</button><span class="m-tag">AI Ethics · Essay 03</span><h2 class="m-title">Surveillance States & AI Ethics</h2><div class="bmr"><span class="bm">📅 Jan 2026</span><span class="bm">⏱ 5 min</span></div></div><div class="m-prog" id="mp-b3"></div><div class="m-body"><div class="prose"><p>There is a version of AI-powered surveillance that sounds almost reasonable: cameras identifying suspects, algorithms detecting terror networks. The problem is these capabilities are structurally indistinguishable from those that enable authoritarianism at industrial scale.</p><blockquote>When a government installs a facial recognition network, it isn't just making a technology purchase — it is making a political choice about the kind of society it intends to govern.</blockquote><h3>As a Builder</h3><p>The computer vision techniques I use in GeoVision — object detection, spatial mapping — are not inherently benign or malicious. Their character is determined entirely by the governance under which they operate. That's a responsibility every AI practitioner needs to carry consciously.</p></div></div></div></div>

<div class="modal" id="m-b4" data-t="r"><div class="modal-bg" onclick="CM('m-b4')"></div><div class="modal-box"><div class="m-accent"></div><div class="m-hdr"><button class="m-close" onclick="CM('m-b4')">✕</button><span class="m-tag">Healthcare · IoT · Essay 04</span><h2 class="m-title">Cold Chains, Code & Public Health</h2><div class="bmr"><span class="bm">📅 Mar 2026</span><span class="bm">⏱ 6 min</span></div></div><div class="m-prog" id="mp-b4"></div><div class="m-body"><div class="prose"><p>Every year, ~50% of vaccines are wasted globally. Many trace directly to cold chain failures — vaccines too warm, too cold, unmonitored during transport.</p><blockquote>The technology to solve this problem has existed for years. The gap is not innovation — it is deployment, will, and funding.</blockquote><h3>What VaxSafe Does</h3><p>ESP32+DHT22 edge device monitors in real-time, triggering hardware alerts on breach. Flask AI calculates potency decay. SHA-256 chaining creates an audit trail that cannot be quietly altered.</p></div></div></div></div>

